text: Welcome back. In earlier sessions, I explained that mindfulness is all about the present moment. We tend to live our lives in the past or the future, constantly playing out predictions and possibilities in our head or thinking about past interactions. This plays a useful evolutionary role, allowing us to learn from our experiences and to make decisions about the future, but sometimes we can become stuck in an endless inner monologue that doesn't really help us. When we become aware of our thoughts as they arise, it becomes easier to simply let them go instead of getting caught up in them. This helps us to connect with the present moment. In this way, meditation can bring a sense of tranquility and calm. It can help us to find peace with the things that we cannot change right this moment. Bear this in mind as we start today's session. Find a comfortable position with your hands resting in your lap. Close your eyes. Take some deep breaths, carefully observing each breath. Notice the weight of your body, your legs pressing down against your seat, the feeling of your arms on your legs, and the sensations in your neck, back, and shoulders. Set an intention for today's session and commit fully to this 10 minutes of meditation. Now, let your attention come back to the breath wherever it appears most clearly. You can count the breaths if you find that it helps you maintain your focus. You can stop counting at any time if it becomes distracting. Don't worry if thoughts arise.
